				<div class="elementor-element elementor-element-37f4b28 elementor-widget elementor-widget-text-editor" data-id="37f4b28" data-element_type="widget" data-widget_type="text-editor.default">
				<div class="elementor-widget-container">
								<div class="elementor-text-editor elementor-clearfix">
				<p>Once it completes you need to run ‘Exit’ to stop the daemon and then we need to announce to the world that we are a public node:</p>					</div>
						</div>
				</div>
				<div class="elementor-element elementor-element-aea54cd elementor-widget elementor-widget-code-highlight" data-id="aea54cd" data-element_type="widget" data-widget_type="code-highlight.default">
				<div class="elementor-widget-container">
					<div class="prismjs-tomorrow copy-to-clipboard ">
			<pre data-line="" class="highlight-height language-markup ">
				<code readonly="true" class="language-markup">
					<xmp>./arqmad --public-node --restricted-rpc --rpc-bind-ip 0.0.0.0 --confirm-external-bind</xmp>
				</code>
			</pre>
		</div>
				</div>
				</div>
				<div class="elementor-element elementor-element-6d858aa elementor-widget elementor-widget-text-editor" data-id="6d858aa" data-element_type="widget" data-widget_type="text-editor.default">
				<div class="elementor-widget-container">
								<div class="elementor-text-editor elementor-clearfix">
				<p>Remember that if you are running a testnet node, do not forget to add the flag at the end. Once it syncs you can close the tmux window and check the connection with your desktop Electron wallet by entering your remote node IP address in the address field and connecting as a remote node. Now you don’t need to store your blockchain on your local PC and use the one you are operating on your remote node that others can now access. If you plan to run a mainnet and testnet node on the same VPS, make sure to copy the folder with your binaries on the desktop so that you can run two tmux windows and two different daemons at the same time.</p>					</div>
						</div>
				</div>
